##Emergency self-rescue in a 24-hour bookstore outbreak

REPORTER: Editor Ma Yue: Ya Han Xiang

“

Guangzhou's first 24 hour bookstore turned off its lights for the first time. The fragile brick-and-mortar Bookstore Industry will also face an existential crisis.

”

“

Guangzhou's first 24 hour bookstore turned off its lights for the first time. The fragile brick-and-mortar Bookstore Industry will also face an existential crisis.

”

On February 24, the day of February 2, the one-way Street Bookstore, co-founded by Xu Zhiyuan, launched a crowdfunding appeal on social networks.

Only one of the four remaining brick and mortar bookstores in the 15 year old bookstore brand, Beijing's Chaoyang Joy City, is open for business, and revenue is expected to plummet by as much as 80 percent in February compared with previous years, it's a dead end.

"The pain and anxiety of every ordinary person is our common destiny at this moment, " the letter said.

The impact of the outbreak on the real sector is clear. Physical bookstores emit far less sound than the restaurant industry's loud burr. Of course, it's also because restaurants can sell vegetables, can deliver food, because it is a necessity of life, but books are not.

At 10 p.m. on Feb. 4, employees at the 1200 bookshop on Guangzhou Sports East road began closing.

Daytime traffic has dropped off precipitously. The evening scene in this southern city is over, with sporadic shoppers walking out the door and the masked clerk nodding at each other, "be safe. "

Guangzhou's first 24 hour bookstore turned off its lights for the first time.

When the situation began to get serious, the bookstore owner Liu Er Xi was still abroad. On the eve of the Spring Festival, he went on a planned trip to visit a local Los Angeles brick and mortar bookstore. He began to feel nervous about the news of the domestic epidemic prevention upgrade.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
1200 bookshop photo: 1200 bookshop wechat account

It's a sudden change. Business as usual was slammed by the outbreak, and throughout the Spring Festival and the first two weeks of February, more than half of his stores across the country were closed, with no source of income. Stores that barely stay open are struggling to generate even a tenth of their usual income. Not surprisingly, all stores will lose money in February.

The Spring Festival is usually the most vulnerable time of the year for the brick-and-mortar Bookstore Industry.

Throughout January, in addition to payroll, most bookstores were preparing for the Spring Festival and the start of the school year, buying stock and paying suppliers. Small and medium-sized bookstores in particular, if there is no income, rent, wages, loans, each is becoming a crushing burden on them.

For the first time in the six years since he started the store, Liu, who had contacted his landlord to try to get a rental waiver, felt, "maybe this is a life-and-death situation. "

"everyone feels that the next thing to go out of business is to lay off the employees, and they are about to lose their lives, " said Sun Qian, the founder of the National Federation of brick-and-mortar Bookstores, who was one of the first to see the crisis in the industry's concentration. Throughout the Spring Festival, the bookstore group of peers are singing the voice of doom.

On the second day of the Lunar New Year, she saw a peer Zeng Feng wrote a Book Industry People's Spring Festival Capriccio, Call Bookstore self-help. He then decided to launch an investigation into the current state of bookstores. "The first is to let people know that you are not the only one who is injured, and the second is to let people know that we all care about the bookstore. We need to boost our confidence first, " Sun told interface news.

By February 5th, with 1,021 questionnaires received nationwide, Sun and Zeng released a report. They found that more than 90% of bookstores had closed, more than 99% of brick and mortar bookstores currently had no regular revenue, and 79.04% of brick and mortar bookstores had less than three months of funding.

"It is almost certain that the recovery period of brick-and-mortar bookstores since 2013 will come to an end, and there will be a wide range of emergency adjustments and even closures of small and medium-sized brick-and-mortar bookstores in the near future, " the report said, "brick-and-mortar bookstores need self-diagnosis, prescriptions and self-help. "

Seeing the industry report, Liu Er Xi, also in Los Angeles, had an emergency meeting with 10 colleagues to figure out what to do next. The coffee business, which used to account for 40% of revenue, can't do it. Books don't rot in the ground like fruits and vegetables, but every day they sit on shelves and stacked in a warehouse, the store gets another day without running water.

Unable to return to work, workers are worried about the current epidemic, but also about future livelihoods.

Liu Er Xi once said that he did not agree with the expression of "too sad" in physical bookstores, "In the early years, when traditional bookstores were facing mass extinction, there was a natural feeling of regret when they were facing extinction, which was exacerbated by a lot of sad media reports, " he said, "Sadness is inevitable. We just don't want to overplay it. Life has to go on and try to be optimistic. It's more worthwhile to explore how to change and Cope and look to the future. "

But for now, his need to survive has led him to look online.

At 11:55 pm on February 15, Liu Erxi sent a distress letter to readers for the first time on the wechat public account of the 1200 bookshop, "For six years, the bookstore has been lit 24 hours a day, and the 1200 bookshop, which has never been closed at night, has been turned off at night. We are very concerned that if this situation continues any longer, the lights in the bookstore will go out during the day."

Through a wechat APP, readers can buy a 1200 bookshop value card, a canvas bag for literary creation, or a "blind selection bag" containing books and literary creation, bookstores try to match everyone's needs.

Thanks to the bookstore's wechat account, which has amassed more than 100,000 followers, the article quickly garnered more than 100,000 views. "Come on, it's not embarrassing to save yourself, " the reader wrote. "please hang in there until the epidemic is over and I'll meet you in Guangzhou. "

As a result of the cancellation of the direct flight, Liu Er Xi finally returned to Guangzhou from Thailand, bringing back at the same time, as well as 2000 masks purchased overseas with the help of friends. Orders for WECHAT APP books topped 2,000, and Wenchuang canvas bags sold more than 1,000.

The coffee area and the floor were filled with books, and everyone's workload suddenly increased. As soon as he returned to the store, he and the staff were busy selecting, packing and delivering books.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo: 1200 bookshop wechat account

Brick-and-mortar bookstores are among the least profitable of all retail businesses. Traditional bookstores, especially small and medium-sized bookstores, it is difficult to e-commerce platform in the price of any competitive advantage. In addition to the financial pressure, the main business is single, less revenue source is also a problem, "we have done a survey in the industry, if the income from selling books accounts for more than 30% , it must be a loss. " Sun Qian told interface news.

Most owners who want to open a bookstore do so out of love.

The idea for the 24 hour bookstore came from the name of a bookstore called 11200 bookshop, which was founded 1200 kilometers around the Taiwan island in China. He was "shocked" by taxis lining up in front of the 24/7's Chengpin Bookstore at 2 pm, and he was drawn to the human touch.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A place for backpackers to rest, photo: 1200 bookshop wechat account

When he returned to Guangzhou in 2014, he found a shop in the neighborhood where he lived, a storefront filled with fireworks. Later, as the business expanded, several branches of 1200 bookshop opened in the business centers of Guangzhou and Shenzhen. However, the double happiness keeps the head office a 24/7, "lighting a late-night lamp for a city" , holding various cultural salons such as reading, watching movies, concerts, etc. , the "late night story" , which runs from 12 pm to 2 am every Saturday night, also continues to be updated. Also, there will be a place for backpackers to spend the night.

"one-third of our customers come often, and some people like to stay overnight, " Liu Er Xi told interface news, "I've always thought of it as an ideal world for me, as an independent bookstore, " she says

As of February 24,1200 bookshop's main store was still 24/7, with one still closed.
